-- Sub-Sahara Africa Stocks: Fan Milk, Guaranty Trust, StanChart
-- B y   V i n c e n t   N w a n m a   a n d   J a s o n   M c l u r e
-- 2010-12-14T17:11:23Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-12-14/sub-sahara-african-equities-fan-milk-guaranty-trust-standard-chartered.html
Mauritius’s  SEMDEX Index  declined
for a fourth day, dropping 0.1 percent to 1,915.28, the lowest
in two weeks, by the 1:30 p.m. close in Port Louis. The  Ghana
Stock Exchange All-Share Index  declined 1.1 percent to 7,114.73
by the 1 p.m. close in Accra.  The  Nigerian Stock Exchange All-Share Index  advanced 0.8
percent to 24,306.8, by the close at 2.30 p.m. in Lagos, the
commercial capital, according to exchange’s website.  Namibia’s  FTSE/Namibia Overall Index  was unchanged at
835.98 at the 5 p.m. close in Windhoek. Kenya’s  All-Share Index 
fell 0.1 percent to 78.66 at the 3 p.m. close in Nairobi.  The following shares rose or fell in sub-Saharan Africa,
excluding South Africa. Stock symbols are in parentheses.  Fan Milk Ltd.  (GML GN), a Ghanaian producer of yogurt and
ice cream, climbed the most in six years as investors expect the
company’s sales to increase. The stock jumped 15 percent, or 26
pesewas, to 2.02 cedis by the 1 p.m. close in Accra.  “During the fourth quarter they sell a lot more products
because it’s the dry season,” said Enyonam Dagadu, head of
brokerage at African Alliance Securities Ghana Ltd., in a phone
interview today from Accra. “During the Christmas festivities, a
lot more people go out and buy ice cream.”  Guaranty Trust Bank Plc  (GUARANTY NL) rose to a six-week
high as investors bet Nigeria’s third-biggest lender’s return on
investment this year will outperform the rest of the industry,
Stanbic IBTC Bank said. The stock gained 50 kobo, or 3 percent,
to close at 17.10 naira, the highest since Oct. 29.  Nigerian Bottling Co.  (NBC NL), which bottles Coca-Cola
products in Africa’s most-populous nation, advanced 1.5 naira,
or 5 percent, to 31.53 naira, after Coca-Cola Hellenic Bottling
Co. said it is offering 94 million euros ($126 million) to buy
the 33.6 percent stake it doesn’t already own in the company.  Standard Chartered Bank Kenya Ltd.  (SCBL KN), Kenya’s
second-biggest lender, declined for a second trading day as
investors sold the stock to pay for their vacations, said  George Bodo , an analyst at Genghis Capital Ltd. The stock declined 5
shillings, or 2 percent, to 251 shillings.  “It is purely retail investors pulling out to finance their
holidays,” Bodo said. “It has been one of the star performers
this year and there is nothing to cause worry.”  To contact the reporters on this story:
